shared_text:
Learning Wild
March 14 at 3:58 PM ¬∑

You are going to come across a lot of app based websites and teacherprenuers that are going to try and capitalize off of the sudden catapult of children into home based settings knowing you need to keep your children busy while you may be working from home. They will tell you to buy their packets of premade worksheets and activity ideas. They will tell you thousands of other children have learned to read with their app. ‚Å£
‚Å£
Don‚Äôt fall for it. Young children don‚Äôt need worksheets or apps to learn. All you need to do is let them play. With activities they choose. Indoors or out. That‚Äôs it. That‚Äôs the secret to teaching a preschooler. And if you don‚Äôt believe it, send me a dm and I‚Äôll fill your inbox with articles and research galore to prove it.

Hey everybody! My name is Tina Farr and I need some help.
But first, I want to give a HUGE shout out to all the parents and my fellow teachers for doing an amazing job this week! It's hard I know, but please know that we miss your kiddos more than you know!

I am a preschool teacher at Singing Hills Elementary (Frogs). I got this idea from a friend in TN, then I saw on the news this morning they are doing it in the Thornton area.

One of my classes FAVORITE books is "We're Going on a Bear Hunt" by Michael Rosen. I am asking the community if they would be so kind as to put a bear in their window... in their car... something for these kiddos to do that they can stay in their car for.. I know I live a little further out of town so I am going to dig in my Christmas box to find an inflatable.

Please help out the littles by doing this! THANK YOU EVERYONE!

post_text: Our students enjoyed the trip and learning more about government! Thanks!
shared_text:
18th Judicial District Attorney's Office - Colorado
February 13 at 1:42 PM ¬∑

On Wednesday we hosted Elizabeth Schools students from teacher John Loutzenhiser's high school class. The students spent the day in our Douglas County office learning about what we do and observing county court proceedings (and eating pizza with us for lunch).

District Attorney George Brauchler welcomed the students in the morning, and chiefs John Kellner and Amy Ferrin worked with them during the day.

We hope they enjoyed their field trip as much as we did!

post_text: Big thanks to Elizabeth Fire & Rescue for training our staff this morning on patient transport carriers. The goal is to be able to equip our staff to know how to evacuate individuals unable to move under their own power from different floors, when stairs are the only means for evacuation. Training will continue at both EHS and Frontier.
shared_text:
Elizabeth Fire Rescue
February 13 at 4:53 PM ¬∑

Elizabeth Fire has partnered with the Elizabeth Schools to provide training to staff on how to respond in certain emergency situations. The "Stop the Bleed" Program teaches staff how to respond to severely bleeding victims. They gain the ability to recognize life-threatening bleeding and intervene effectively. The Mega Mover training taught school staff how to safely transport injured victims thus reducing the possibility of further injury. Firefighters are excited to be able to train with teachers to bring progressive techniques to keep our kids safe.

post_text: WOW! EMS Sixth grade students from Christy Banks science classes recently enjoyed 'virtual field trips' to the American Museum of Natural History in New York City, along with a quick trip around the sun. Due in part to the 2018 Mill Levy Override, teachers in Elizabeth Schools now have access to several virtual reality kits (students wear special goggles and are virtually transported to a different location). Students observed dinosaur fossils on display at the museum, as well as interacted with a MERGE cube to explore the sun and solar system. #SchoolsSoCool #ChooseElizabethSchools

The University of Colorado Denver (https://www.facebook.com/UCDenver/) will host the state‚Äôs best and brightest high school students this summer, and we want you to apply! The Colorado Student Leaders Institute (https://www.facebook.com/ColoradoGovernorsSchool/) is a month-long, state sponsored program where students live and study on a Colorado campus. Participants earn three hours of college credit toward one of two majors‚ÄîInternational Social Studies or STEAM (Science, Technology, Engineering, Arts, & Math‚Äîand complete three hands-on projects.

post_text:
Choose Elizabeth Schools! #WhereEveryoneKnowsYourName
Top-rated, high performing rural school district known for its caring culture & student-focused philosophy, located about 45 miles southeast of Denver.

**Small class sizes (average K-12 class is 23 students)
**Extensive student leadership opportunities in all grades
**Half & full-day preschool programs; FREE all day kindergarten
**Strong performing arts programs at middle & high school levels
**STEM & Robotics offered K-12
**Competitive, integrated middle school sports leads to 18 high school varsity teams
**Experienced staff known for integrity, passion, & excellence

Can't make this Open House? Visit http://bit.ly/ESopenhouse and schedule a tour at your convenience.

Margaret Anne is a young girl who has never won anything in her life and suddenly finds herself as a participant in the upcoming "Miss Spell Contest" representing two spelling bees from an organization known as Rebels Without a Clue. The two spelling bees, 2 Bee and Not 2 Bee, take Margaret Anne to the Land of Spell where she is introduced to the queen and various characters who help her with basic rules of spelling. Margaret Anne not only becomes a better speller, she learns to overcome self-doubt even at the risk of being wrong. Tickets are $5.

post_text: Did you know September is "Fruit & Veggies - More Matters" Month? The purpose is to highlight the benefits of eating a healthy, balance diet that includes a lot of fruit and vegetables. The Elizabeth School District Wellness Committee recommends learning more on the health benefits and tips on how to make them part of your daily meal/snack routine. Click here for more info: https://fruitsandveggies.org/ #VeggiesMatter #LoveourFruit

Over 100 6th grade students, 14 parent chaperones, 4 EMS staff, and hundreds of luggage and camping gear were packed into 3 school buses today to head up into the mountains for the 6th Grade Outdoor Education Trip in Bailey, CO. Students will stay in cabins and enjoy an unforgettable outdoor learning experience improving social and personal skills, working cooperatively, and getting to know themselves.

post_text: EHS Seniors Mallory Ricker, Anna Mowbray, and Blake Strickland (LtoR) are excited to be back at school and do all the 'senior stuff' this year. Mallory and Anna are also part of the EHS Flight Crew which helps new EHS students navigate the school and classes. "I like helping new kids, share advice, and make their high school experience a great one," says Mowbray. Ricker added, "I really like meeting all the new kids and then seeing them around school throughout the year." #senioritis #loveyourschool #whereeveryoneknowsyourname #firstdayofschool
